<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / International Company News: Viacom profits up seven-fold in
third quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Acquisitions helped Viacom, the fast-growing US entertainment and media
group, to a seven-fold rise in earnings a share in the third quarter.
The results included a first-time contribution from Paramount
Communications, acquired for Dollars 9.6bn earlier this year.
However, they have yet to reflect Viacom's Dollars 8.4bn acquisition of
Blockbuster, the video and music retailer, or its Dollars 1.1bn sale of
Madison Square Garden.
Net earnings were Dollars 327.3m, compared with Dollars 30.9m, before
extraordinary items, and earnings a share were Dollars 1.32 against 18
cents. Sales in the quarter were Dollars 2.1bn, up from Dollars 508m.
Mr Frank Biondi, president, said the inclusion of Blockbuster would improve
results further. 'Our prospects for the fully integrated company, when all
our operations are reflected and we begin to benefit from the many
cross-divisional activities now under way, are tremendously promising,' he
said.
Blockbuster's sales in the nine months to September were up 42 per cent to
Dollars 2.1bn and net profits by 26 per cent to Dollars 360.2m.
Earnings from Viacom's television networks were up strongly, largely because
of higher advertising rates and subscription revenues. However, profits from
cable TV fell by 33 per cent, after a 12 per cent fall in the previous year,
as a result of government-imposed cuts in cable rates.
Among the activities acquired with Paramount, feature films earned Dollars
86m on sales of Dollars 431m in the quarter (no comparable figures were
given).
Viacom said the quarter had been helped by such US releases as Naked Gun 33
1/3 and Forrest Gump. Television programming earned Dollars 18.7m, affected
by lower syndication sales. Paramount Parks earned Dollars 30.3m, affected
by lower attendances and higher costs.
The publishing division, also acquired with Paramount, earned Dollars 175m
on sales of Dollars 701m. Results were helped by Paramount's own Dollars
553m purchase of Macmillan, part of the bankrupt Maxwell empire, at the
start of the year.
</TEXT>
