<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Major attacks MPs with too many paid interests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major last night underlined his determination to shake off the
charges of sleaze that have damaged his government by launching a robust
attack on MPs who take on too many paid outside interests.
The prime minister used his annual speech at the Lord Mayor's banquet in
London to defend the right of MPs to have outside interests and to argue
that the UK would not benefit if parliament were populated by 'wholly
professional' politicians.
He said, however, that Westminster should not be 'a hiring fair'. Parliament
should not be a 'way' to other jobs, 'as frankly it sometimes has been'.
Speaking as MPs prepare to return to Westminster for tomorrow's Queen's
Speech detailing next year's legislative programme, Mr Major emphasised that
the recently established Nolan committee would have a continuing role in
policing standards in British public life.
The body's task was not just to meet 'immediate questions', he said, but 'to
act as a running authority of reference - almost, you might say, an ethical
workshop called in to do running repairs'.
In a speech billed by Downing Street as more than usually his own creation,
Mr Major said it was important to attract the 'right people' into public
service and urged commentators to use their 'very great' freedom to attack
and expose with responsibility.
'We no longer live nowadays, thank goodness, in a 'deference society', where
you are respected for who you are not what you are,' he said. 'But let's not
swing too far in the opposite direc-tion.'
Acknowledging the need to improve the accountability of the public service,
he said that government had been 'too secret too long'. 'It is damaging if
there appears to be some kind of inside track - a gulf between those who
know how to play the system and others who do not,' he said. His sympathy
was with those on 'the outside track'.
Mr Major was speaking as it emerged that one feature of the Commons debate
after the Queen's Speech may be a speech by Mr Neil Hamilton, the former
corporate affairs minister, who resigned last month following allegations of
impropriety which he strongly denies.
Friends of Mr Hamilton said last night that he was 'minded' to try to take
part in the debate. But they added that he would not say anything which was
likely to militate against his resuming ministerial office.
Mr John Prescott, Labour's deputy leader, attacked the speech as
'depressingly complacent'. He said Mr Major was 'whistling in the dark'.
In a speech that ranged more widely than the occasion's traditional focus on
foreign affairs, Mr Major also commented on the economy, business and
Northern Ireland.
Welcoming recent remarks on the need for responsibility in setting executive
pay levels, he said there was 'no doubting the resentment that large and
often unjustified pay rises' could cause.
He said British capitalism had become 'capitalism with a conscience, but
there was still more that business could do to improve its image'.
</TEXT>
