<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two things stand out tonight: Barbara Windsor (the Carry On mode is
inescapable). The busty cockney sparrer has little of interest to say, but
that's to be expected from Without Walls: The Obituary Show (C4 9.00), with
one of those fearsomely humourless commissioning editors who persistently
pronounce obiter dicta on humour. On tonight's showing you might think she's
been rather lucky. So perhaps has Muriel Gray, extolling (or not) the Range
Rover in Ride On (C4 8.00): a figure no less grotesque but rather less
self-knowledgeable.
From sex, albeit self-parodying, to our other preoccupation, money. How to
Win the Lottery (BBC1 9.30) is also a lesson in how to survive that
sometimes pyrrhic victory. Inane purchases, litigious relatives, the quest
for wealth sliding effortlessly into the slot once occupied by organised
religion.
Those who remember the young John Pilger's blend of righteousness,
theatrical anger and occasionally woolly thinking can skip Network First
(ITV 10.40) with a clear conscience. Some of that youthful hysteria would be
welcome in this plod through the British arms trade.
</TEXT>
