<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Producers' body to accuse BBC of unfair practices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pact, the main body representing independent television and film producers,
will this week formally accuse the BBC of being guilty of a restraint of
trade.
Mr Tom Gutteridge, chairman of Pact - the Producers Alliance for Cinema and
TV - will make the complaint of unfairness to Mr Will Wyatt, managing
director of BBC Television.
Pact, which represents more than 800 independent production companies,
claims independents are denied fair access to programme proposals.
In the ITV system, independent producers have the right to take their ideas
directly to the Network Centre, the main programme-commissioning body for
the national ITV network. This right is underpinned by an agreement
monitored by the Office of Fair Trading, whose role was spelled out in the
1990 Broadcasting Act. No such formal rules govern the relations between the
BBC and independents.
The main complaint is that independents do not have guaranteed access to the
BBC's channel controllers, Mr Alan Yentob at BBC 1 and Mr Michael Jackson at
BBC 2. Ideas have to be filtered first through heads of department, who are
at the same time promoting in-house ideas.
Pact believes this amounts to a conflict of interest and fears many ideas
from independents never reach the channel controllers.
The alliance claims this lack of direct access amounts to a restraint of
trade, and has communicated its worries to the government. The National
Heritage Department is in the process of drawing up legislation for the
renewal of the BBC's royal charter, which runs out at the end of 1996.
Pact has not ruled out taking the issue to the OFT if the BBC does not
change its procedures.
</TEXT>
