<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Convenience food sales rise steeply
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ready-made meals comprised almost 35 per cent of the average household's
food bill last year, a rise of nearly 10 per cent since the early 1980s,
according to the 1993 National Food Survey.
Sales of pizzas, frozen chips, crisps and other potato snacks also rose,
while consumption of beef and lamb has dropped, according to the survey,
which was published yesterday by the Ministry of Agriculture Fisheries and
Food.
The Meat and Livestock Commission said high lamb prices probably accounted
for the drop in consumption, while beef sales had been influenced by adverse
publicity about Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy - mad cow disease.
The survey showed that fresh potatoes accounted for 40 per cent of household
consumption by weight in 1993 compared with 48 per cent in 1983, but frozen
vegetable sales rose.
Fresh fruit sales were the same, except for bananas, which grew in
popularity.
Consumers in the south-east and East Anglia ate most frozen foods, while
shoppers in Scotland and the north of England spent most on convenience
foods.
The Fruit and Vegetable Information Bureau said bananas were increasingly
popular because they were easy to peel. 'Vegetables like cauliflower and
broccoli which are easy to prepare and cook are also increasing in
popularity. But it's not the same with root vegetables which take longer to
cook, which is a pity because they are cheaper and very nutritious.
'Salad vegetables are also selling well because they are easy to prepare and
go with many convenience meals like pizzas.'
Families were drinking less full-fat milk than skimmed and fat-reduced milk.
Cheese was also less popular, the survey said.
The survey also showed:
Bread sales - particularly white bread - were lower in the south of England
than in the north and Midlands.
Consumption of frozen cakes and pastry increased, while biscuit and
breakfast cereal sales fell.
Convenience foods provided 28 per cent of the total intake of energy in
1993, up from 20 per cent in 1983.
Spending on food was 2.2 per cent higher in 1993 than in 1992 at Pounds
13.21 per person per week.
National Food Survey 1993. Annual Report on Household Food Consumption and
Expenditure. Published by the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food,
10 Whitehall Place, SW1A. 071 270 8080.
</TEXT>
