<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Howard tries to defuse row over crime plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, yesterday tried to defuse a growing
row over cuts in compensation for crime victims by announcing that they
would have a greater say over when prisoners should be released.
Following a court ruling last week that he had acted unlawfully in cutting
levels of compensation for victims, Mr Howard said he would set up a Prison
Helpline on which crime victims could state why particular prisoners should
not be released from jail.
Mr Howard vigorously defended recent cuts in the Criminal Injuries
Compensation Scheme, in spite of a High Court ruling last week that he had
abused his powers by introducing new tariffs.
In a bid to reassert his authority on the issue, he claimed all the changes
were made after taking legal advice and he renewed his pledge to fight the
Court of Appeal ruling in the House of Lords.
However, Mr Howard immediately came under fire from prison governors and
pressure groups who argued that they had not been consulted over the
creation of the helpline and that it was an unworkable idea.
Mr Harry Fletcher, assistant general secretary of the National Probation
Officers' Association, said a hotline was totally impractical with some
140,000 cases of home and temporary leave each year.
'Who on earth is to tell the victims of crime that the prisoners are coming
up for consideration? Certainly the probation officers can't do it because
there are no resources,' he said on BBC Radio 4's prog-ramme The World at
One.
Mr Paul Cavadino, chair of the Penal Affairs Consortium, an alliance of 23
organisations concerned with the penal system, said that it would be wrong
to refuse parole or home leave 'simply because the victim felt that the
offender should be punished more severely'.
Mr Howard, addressing the Victim Support organisation in London, said it had
been difficult for victims of crime to get their voices heard.
'I also know that some victims of crime have seen or been contacted by
serving prisoners - people are understandably afraid or distressed by that
contact,' he said.
He added: 'In future, victims will be able to pass on those concerns
immediately and confidentially in the knowledge that something will be
done.'
However, his difficulties over the victim compensation issue have further
undermined his authority as home secretary after a year of difficulties over
the Criminal Justice Bill.
</TEXT>
