<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Skills strategy launched for construction sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The construction industry yesterday launched recruitment targets for its new
skills training strategy in a move to standardise requirements across the
industry.
The Construction Industry Training Board said it planned to recruit 10,200
trainees in 1994-1995, rising to 17,000 by 1996-97, in anticipation of a 1
per cent annual growth in construction output.
However, Sir Clifford Chetwood, the board's chairman, said this would only
cover half the number of construction employees lost from the industry each
year through death or retirement.
Warwick University's Institute for Employment Research forecast recently
that there would be 1.4m employees in the construction industry by 1997.
Sir Clifford said half of all construction workers currently had no formal
qualifications.
The board's strategy for training skilled craftsmen, such as carpenters,
bricklayers and joiners, as well as manual labourers provides six
alternative 'flexible routes' to training, which accommodate changes in
education and the industry itself.
Recognising the increasing use of self-employed and labour-only
sub-contractors rather than employee craftsmen, the board has introduced
grants for contractors to provide work experience or apprenticeships.
It will give a Pounds 300 grant per trainee every year to each main
contractor which places a candidate with one of its labour-only
sub-contractors or self-employed workers.
</TEXT>
