<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Ian Craig, architect of FT Statistics structure: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ian Craig, who died in a car accident on Saturday aged 53, was the architect
of some of the most delicate and far-reaching technical changes carried out
at the Financial Times. As systems manager of FT Statistics, he designed a
modern structure for collecting and processing the vast array of market data
printed daily in the FT and distributed to clients.
He did not see every part of this complex operation transferred to the new
suite of databases. But his disciplined mind, rigorous attention to detail
and sheer professionalism not only took the FT's statistical operations from
hot metal printing to the first generation of computerisation but set out an
elegant design that will last well into the next century.
Born in East Lothian, Ian Craig graduated as an engineer and served in the
Queen's Flight of the RAF. He worked in the printing machinery industry
before joining the FT in the mid-1970s when it was first exploring
computerised production. He combined deep knowledge of the intricacies of
typesetting with a creative mastery of computer technology.
The kindest and most considerate of colleagues, he was always as willing to
explain difficult technical issues patiently to lay people as he was open to
new ideas.
Sailing was Ian's spare-time passion, shared with the family he was devoted
to. He leaves a widow, Carol, and their three children, Alastair, Nick and
Sheena.
</TEXT>
<XX>
