<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Government seeks way round Pergau ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain may use its overseas aid budget to fund Malaysia's Pergau dam
project, in spite of a High Court ruling last week that the government had
acted illegally in making such donations.
Amid growing controversy about the link between aid and international arms
deals, officials at the Treasury, Foreign Office and Overseas Development
Administration (ODA) have been examining ways to pay more than Pounds 200m
to Malaysia without contravening the judgment.
The High Court ruled last week that the ODA could not make direct payments
for the Pergau dam project because it does not promote the development of a
country's economy, as required by UK law.
Treasury officials are now examining a scheme whereby the ODA could be
required to make the payments indirectly so that Britain continues to meet a
commitment made by Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, three years ago.
Under the proposal, the cost of Britain's aid donation to Malaysia would be
met from the Treasury's contingency fund. The Treasury would then make
commensurate cuts in the ODA's budget.
The Foreign Office is understood to have warned that this method of paying
the Malaysians could run counter to the spirit of the High Court judgment
and might invoke further legal penalties. However, Foreign Office officials
will be keen to ensure that the payments do not come from their own budget.
Under the agreement with the Malaysian government, the ODA agreed to use its
aid and trade provision to provide Pounds 234m in staged payments to help
build the dam.
The government still has to pay a total of Pounds 216m of these payments,
which meet the costs of borrowing at concessionary interest rates to help
fund the dam. The next payment, of Pounds 15m, is due on December 20.
The controversy over the Pergau dam comes amid speculation that the UK has
used development aid to forge a Pounds 6.1bn arms deal with Indonesia. Last
night Baroness Chalker, the overseas aid minister, denied any connection
between weapons contracts and aid to President Suharto's government.
'Our programme is targeted on human resource development, the environment,
good government and transportation,' she said.
'We have repeatedly expressed our concern about Indonesia's human rights
record. The Indonesian government recognises the need for improvement. I can
confirm that at no stage has there been any linkage between our aid
programme to Indonesia and the sale of arms.'
However, UK military officials are planning a four-month military tour of
Indonesia and other countries in the Asia-Pacific region next year to
promote UK naval equipment. It is understood that Westland-built Lynx
helicopters will be demonstrated to potential buyers.
The aid-for-arms allegations are set to be the focus of a Commons foreign
affairs debate on Thursday, when Mr Hurd will face questions over claims
that the UK's aid budget has been targeted at countries buying military
equipment.
The government is also facing a renewed public challenge over its defence
policy with the launch today of a national campaign against official credit
cover for arms sales.
The campaign over the Export Credits Guarantee Department is being organised
by the World Development Movement, the lobby group which won the High Court
ruling against Mr Hurd over the Pergau dam funding. The group said the
export credits department was being inundated with letters calling for an
end to an estimated Pounds 322m annual subsidy to the defence sector.
</TEXT>
