</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications has been awarded a substantial contract by
Microsoft, the world's largest software house, to develop a data
communications network in Europe and the Asia Pacific region. The UK group
declined yesterday to give the value of the contract but said it ran into
many millions of pounds and was one of the largest international contracts
the company had won.
The network will be used as part of Microsoft's newly announced worldwide
on-line information service, The Microsoft Network, which is expected to
represent a challenge to existing information providers such as Compuserve
and American Online. BT will use Concert, its joint venture with MCI of the
US, to provide the basis of the network. Customers with a personal computer
running Windows 95 and a modem will be able to connect from anywhere in
Europe or Asia/Pacific over the public telephone network to a BT node, and
from there to Microsoft in Seattle over Concert's high-speed lines.
