<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Iraq assures UN over Kuwait
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iraq formally submitted a series of documents affirming its recognition of
Kuwait's sovereignty and the United Nations-designated border between them
to the UN security council yesterday. Mr Tariq Aziz, deputy prime minister,
insisted that this justified an early lifting of the economic embargo, but a
US spokesman said no change was in prospect as the result of the council's
60-day sanctions review period. He also linked Baghdad's belated concession
to the firmness of the US and other council members in response to menacing
Iraqi troop movements near the border last month. Before the US and Britain,
which have veto power, will consider lifting sanctions Iraq must fulfil
other obligations including the return of captured Kuwaiti armaments and
property. There must also be total compliance with the UN commission charged
with eliminating Iraq's nuclear, long-range missile,and chemical and
biological capability.
Mr Aziz's case has not been helped by information from American officials
that funds have still been found to rebuild President Saddam Hussain's
palace and other buildings at a cost of Dollars 1bn (Pounds 610m). Mr Aziz
termed this 'rubbish'.
Ms Madeleine Albright, US representative and council president, who received
the documents from him, acknowledged that members would be very pleased.
Iraq had finally done what the international community had long demanded.
But continuing American scepticism was evident in the brevity and coolness
of the meeting, which lasted barely two minutes and at which Mr Aziz was
characterised as 'not his usual ebullient self'. For the occasion, Ms
Albright wore a brooch in the form of a reptile on her plain blue dress.
This was her response to the recent publication by an Iraqi newspaper of an
unflattering poem in which she was called a snake.
</TEXT>
