<HEADLINE>
FT  15 NOV 94 / Lottery sells 7m tickets in 12 hours: Major tells launch
party all will benefit and country will be richer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Camelot, operator of the UK's first national lottery for more than 150
years, said it was 'absolutely delighted' with sales of more than 7m tickets
in the 12 hours since yesterday's 7am launch.
The total was nearly three times as much as its estimates for the first day.
In some places, people queued outside retail outlets selling the Pounds 1
tickets. More than 10,000 outlets had on-line computer terminals, and a
further 2,500 are expected to be connected before Christmas.
The lottery hopes to raise Pounds 32bn over seven years, with an estimated
Pounds 9bn going to causes such as charities and the arts. It was launched
in London in a marquee in the grounds of the Tower with the help of a string
octet, a group of Morris dancers and a fireworks display.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, pronounced it 'a people's lottery'. He
said everyone would benefit.
At exactly 7am Sir Ron Dearing, the Camelot chairman, pushed a wooden
plunger, apparently to initiate ticket sales around the country. The plunger
was precisely that - and not connected to anything.
Early morning Guests in the grounds of the Tower - there were also official
launches in Belfast, Cardiff and Edinburgh - could not, however, buy
tickets. As a result Mr Major had to be driven to a newsagent in central
London, where he spent Pounds 5 and promised to donate the more than Pounds
2m jackpot to Mencap, the mental health charity, if he won.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, secretary for the national heritage, the department
responsible for the National Lottery, also promised to buy tickets and to
give any winnings to Age Concern.
Mr Dorrell warned he had no early plans to change the rules on how money for
the arts - one of the five beneficiaries - from the proceeds of the lottery
should be used.
Mr Chris Smith, shadow heritage spokesman, welcomed the launch but wanted to
see the benefits felt in every community.
The main questioning voice came from the Salvation Army, which suggested
that punters should give all their lottery stake to charity rather than the
28p in the Pounds 1 that the lottery will give to good causes.
</TEXT>
