<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Equity Markets: Stockholm - Other markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Equities face a volatile week, but whether they move up or down will depend
on the outcome of yesterday's referendum on EU membership and nine-month
figures from several big companies, writes Christopher Brown-Humes.
Two of the industrial heavyweights, Volvo and Ericsson, present their
figures tomorrow and on Thursday respectively.
In Ericsson's case, expectations are running high due to the spectacular
growth in sales of the group's cellular products and a strong set of
eight-month figures from its Finnish rival, Nokia.
Goldman Sachs in London is expecting nine-month profits of SKr3.5bn, up from
SKr1.86bn a year ago, and full-year profits of SKr5.5bn.
AssiDoman and SCA, two of the leading forestry groups, will also announce
figures. With the pulp and paper sector in a clear uptrend, they are
expected to be strong.
SCA, which reports on Friday, is expected to disclose a profit of around
SKr1.6bn. The main interest will be in how its Molnlycke hygiene unit is
weathering increasing competition in the nappies (diapers) market.
Analysts say that whatever the outcome of the referendum, concern about the
state of Sweden's finances will continue to affect equities via the bond
market. Another cloud on the horizon for the export-orientated
multinationals is the strengthening krona, which could harm next year's
earnings significantly if the trend continues.
</TEXT>
