<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / BSkyB to float with 19 on board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An enormous 19-strong board has been created for the Pounds 4bn-Pounds 4.5bn
flotation of satellite broadcaster British Sky Broadcasting, including five
non-executive directors from outside the entertainment industry.
The move, which will more than double the size of the board, will be
outlined today in the pathfinder prospectus. The price range for the shares
is expected to be 233p-268p.
Another point of interest is likely to be the latest BSkyB subscription
figures. By the end of June, BSkyB said it had 3.45m cable and satellite
subscribers. Recent estimates of a 60,000-a-month growth rate would suggest
that demand is slowing. .
The new directors include Sir John Collins, chairman of Vestey Group and
former chief executive of Shell UK, and Mr Dennis Stevenson, chairman of SRU
consultancy and a director of the Tate Gallery as well as Pearson, the media
group that owns the Financial Times.
Mr Sam Chisholm, BSkyB's chief executive, will remain a director but with a
new contract directly with BSkyB. Concern has been expressed that Mr
Chisholm, who has played an important role in BSkyB's turnround, was
contracted to Mr Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation, at present owner of 50
per cent of BSkyB.
Other new non-executives are Mr Geoffrey Bible, chief executive of Philip
Morris, Bass director Mr Philip Bowman and Mr John Thornton of Goldman
Sachs, who set up an auction between News Corp and Pearson over Star TV in
Hong Kong.
The existing two non-executives - Lord St John Stevas and Dame Anne Mueller
 -continue. Mr David Chance, deputy managing director, and Mr Richard
Brooke, finance director, also join the board.
Other News Corp representatives will be Mr Murdoch, Mr Dave Devoe, Mr Gus
Fischer and Mr Arthur Siskind.
On the old BSB side Mr Frank Barlow will remain chairman, Mr Gerry Robinson,
Granada chief executive, will join, as will Mr Jerome Seydoux, Chargeurs
chairman. Mr David Sneddon, chairman of Trinity International, will
represent the old BSB minorities.
News Corp and Telstra in pay-TV venture, Page 21
