<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / NPC to reveal buy-out proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Parking Corporation is set to reveal details of a leveraged buy-out
by venture capital institutions, expected to value the business at about
Pounds 650m. The deal, due to be announced at NPC's annual meeting on
December 5, is likely to be the largest UK venture capital buy-out so far
this year.
Prudential Venture Managers should unveil the agreed purchase of around 72
per cent of NPC's shares, primarily owned by founders Mr Ronald Hobson and
Sir Donald Gosling, and charitable foundations of which they are directors.
NPC owns National Car Parks, the biggest operator of car parks in the UK.
Prudential has brought in backers Charterhouse Development Capital, Cinven,
Electra, Montagu Private Equity, NatWest Ventures and Royal Bank Development
Capital. They are expected to put up about 50 per cent of the cost as
equity. The remainder will be funded by bank debt, to be arranged by a
syndicate led by National Westminster Bank.
The founders sold 28 per cent of the company to a number of financial
institutions in 1986, and these are likely to be offered shares in the new
company, as an alternative to the cash offer.
It is understood that no final agreement on pricing has been reached.
However, due diligence is complete, and NPC has written to shareholders
saying: 'We hope to be able to give shareholders further information at the
AGM', when the final offer should be revealed. Shareholders will also be
asked to approve the adoption of new Articles of Association, paving the way
for a change in ownership.
The letter to shareholders accompanied NPC's latest set of profit figures,
for the year to March 1994. Profits before exceptional items rose from
Pounds 48.6m to Pounds 50.4m. However, total pre-tax profits fell to Pounds
50.5m (Pounds 53.3m).
NPC was set up by Mr Hobson and Sir Donald in 1949, but for the past year
the founders have been keen to sell.
The joint chairmen were keen to ensure continuity for the existing
management and turned down the option of a share disposal, via flotation.
Other offers were received by their advisers, Morgan Grenfell, but the
venture capital consortium put forward the highest bid.
The attraction for the new investors is the strong and predictable cashflow
from the UK's largest car parking group, and the potential earnings growth
offered by its more dynamic subsidiary, Green Flag, which controls National
Breakdown.
Green Flag has been aggressively expanding National Breakdown into Europe,
as well as setting up Home Emergency Service, a domestic repair group. A
separate flotation could be launched once these businesses have matured.
The share price of NPC, which trades on a matched bargain basis, has tailed
off in recent weeks, closing at 537 1/2 p on Friday, compared with a 1994
high of 630p, which followed suggestions of a potential price tag of up to
Pounds 800m. At Friday's closing price, NPC has a market capitalisation of
Pounds 632m.
</TEXT>
