<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The great British public are turning as one to BBC 2's Martin Chuzzlewit
tonight - or are they? Last week's opener tingled with a sense of occasion,
redoubtable British actors who are correctly hatchet-faced in Pinter going
wildly OTT at the nuzzle of a wing-collar or the swing of a corkscrew curl.
Thesps love Dickens and he loved them; no quarrel with the relish of Tom
Wilkinson's magnificent Pecksniff or Paul Scofield's double act as the
ill-matched Chuzzlewit brothers; and watch out for a touching John Mills
tonight. But irritatingly nudging film music and a cautious narrative pace
suggest slower-witted overseas markets are targeted for this slice of
English heritage. It even has a honking case of adenoids, in the form of
young Martin who swallows his words and breathes them out through his nose
(9.30).
From costume capers to Granada's launch of The War Machine, ITV's week-long
look at the arms trade. Tonight's World in Action coasts in on the scummy
crest of the sleaze wave, promising revelations of corruption among the men
from the ministry and a major British company (8.30).
</TEXT>
